<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910314-0049</DOCNO><DOCID>910314-0049.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- USX Corp.:   United Steelworkers Clear   Three-Year Pact With USX</HL><DATE>03/14/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><CO>   X LABOR J.KOB BS</CO><IN>OIL, SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)</IN><LP>   Members of the United Steelworkers of America, asexpected, approved a three-year labor contract with USX Corp.   The pact, which covers about 17,500 employees, boostswages $1.50 an hour over the life of the contract andrestores $1 an hour in wage sacrifices made in the recessionof the early 1980s. About 2,600 workers at USS/Kobe, a jointventure of Pittsburgh-based USX and Japan's Kobe Steel,approved a similar pact.</LP><TEXT>   The USX contract also contains strong language protectingunion members should USX sell all or part of its steeloperations.   With the approval of the pact, the union has largelysucceeded in establishing wage and benefit parity among majorU.S. steelmakers. The union signed a similar so-calledpattern contract over the past two years with other majorsteelmakers, including Bethlehem Steel Corp.   The USX contract, which is retroactive to Feb. 1, doescontain some differences. Instead of granting cost-of-livingincreases, USX agreed to a $2,500 bonus over three years.Also, instead of agreeing to shoulder 50% of a retiree'soptional major medical premiums, the company agreed toincrease monthly pension payments $50 a couple over threeyears.</TEXT></DOC>